[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT is trained by masked token prediction and next sentence prediction.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] With this training, BERT learns contextual, latent representations of tokens in their context, similar to ELMo and GPT-2.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] It found applications for many natural language processing tasks, such as coreference resolution and polysemy resolution.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] It improved on ELMo and spawned the study of "BERTology", which attempts to interpret what is learned by BERT.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT was originally implemented in the English language at two model sizes, BERTBASE (110 million parameters) and BERTLARGE (340 million parameters).
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Both were trained on the Toronto BookCorpus (800M words) and English Wikipedia (2,500M words).
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] On March 11, 2020, 24 smaller models were released, the smallest being BERTTINY with just 4 million parameters.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT is an "encoder-only" transformer architecture.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The task head is necessary for pre-training, but it is often unnecessary for so-called "downstream tasks," such as question answering or sentiment classification.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Instead, one removes the task head and replaces it with a newly initialized module suited for the task, and finetune the new module.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The latent vector representation of the model is directly fed into this new module, allowing for sample-efficient transfer learning.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] This section describes the embedding used by BERTBASE.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The other one, BERTLARGE, is similar, just larger.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The tokenizer of BERT is WordPiece, which is a sub-word strategy like byte-pair encoding.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Its vocabulary size is 30,000, and any token not appearing in its vocabulary is replaced by `[UNK]` ("unknown").
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The first layer is the embedding layer, which contains three components: token type embeddings, position embeddings, and segment type embeddings.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The three embedding vectors are added together representing the initial token representation as a function of these three pieces of information.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] After embedding, the vector representation is normalized using a LayerNorm operation, outputting a 768-dimensional vector for each input token.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] After this, the representation vectors are passed forward through 12 Transformer encoder blocks, and are decoded back to 30,000-dimensional vocabulary space using a basic affine transformation layer.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The encoder stack of BERT has 2 free parameters: L , the number of layers, and H , the *hidden size*.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] There are always $H/64$ self-attention heads, and the feed-forward/filter size is always $4H$ .
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] By varying these two numbers, one obtains an entire family of BERT models.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The notation for encoder stack is written as L/H.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] For example, BERTBASE is written as 12L/768H, BERTLARGE as 24L/1024H, and BERTTINY as 2L/128H.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] In masked language modeling, 15% of tokens would be randomly selected for masked-prediction task, and the training objective was to predict the masked token given its context.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The reason not all selected tokens are masked is to avoid the dataset shift problem.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The dataset shift problem arises when the distribution of inputs seen during training differs significantly from the distribution encountered during inference.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] A trained BERT model might be applied to word representation (like Word2Vec), where it would be run over sentences not containing any `[MASK]` tokens.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] It is later found that more diverse training objectives are generally better.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] As an illustrative example, consider the sentence "my dog is cute".
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] It would first be divided into tokens like "my1 dog2 is3 cute4".
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Then a random token in the sentence would be picked.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] After processing the input text, the model's 4th output vector is passed to its decoder layer, which outputs a probability distribution over its 30,000-dimensional vocabulary space.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Given two sentences, the model predicts if they appear sequentially in the training corpus, outputting either `[IsNext]` or `[NotNext]`.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] During training, the algorithm sometimes samples two sentences from a single continuous span in the training corpus, while at other times, it samples two sentences from two discontinuous spans.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The first sentence starts with a special token, `[CLS]` (for "classify").
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The two sentences are separated by another special token, `[SEP]` (for "separate").
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] After processing the two sentences, the final vector for the `[CLS]` token is passed to a linear layer for binary classification into `[IsNext]` and `[NotNext]`.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT is meant as a general pretrained model for various applications in natural language processing.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] In the original paper, all parameters of BERT are fine-tuned, and recommended that, for downstream applications that are text classifications, the output token at the `[CLS]` input token is fed into a linear-softmax layer to produce the label outputs.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The original code base defined the final linear layer as a "pooler layer", in analogy with global pooling in computer vision, even though it simply discards all output tokens except the one corresponding to `[CLS]`.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT was trained on the BookCorpus (800M words) and a filtered version of English Wikipedia (2,500M words) without lists, tables, and headers.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Training BERTBASE on 4 cloud TPU (16 TPU chips total) took 4 days, at an estimated cost of 500 USD.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Training BERTLARGE on 16 cloud TPU (64 TPU chips total) took 4 days.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Language models like ELMo, GPT-2, and BERT, spawned the study of "BERTology", which attempts to interpret what is learned by these models.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Their performance on these natural language understanding tasks are not yet well understood.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Several research publications in 2018 and 2019 focused on investigating the relationship behind BERT's output as a result of carefully chosen input sequences, analysis of internal vector representations through probing classifiers, and the relationships represented by attention weights.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The high performance of the BERT model could also be attributed to the fact that it is bidirectionally trained.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] This means that BERT, based on the Transformer model architecture, applies its self-attention mechanism to learn information from a text from the left and right side during training, and consequently gains a deep understanding of the context.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] For example, the word *fine* can have two different meanings depending on the context (**I feel** fine **today**, **She has** fine **blond hair**).
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT considers the words surrounding the target word *fine* from the left and right side.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] However it comes at a cost: due to encoder-only architecture lacking a decoder, BERT can't be prompted and can't generate text, while bidirectional models in general do not work effectively without the right side, thus being difficult to prompt.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] As an illustrative example, if one wishes to use BERT to continue a sentence fragment "Today, I went to", then naively one would mask out all the tokens as "Today, I went to `[MASK]` `[MASK]` `[MASK]` ...
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] `[MASK]` ." where the number of `[MASK]` is the length of the sentence one wishes to extend to.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] However, this constitutes a dataset shift, as during training, BERT has never seen sentences with that many tokens masked out.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] More sophisticated techniques allow text generation, but at a high computational cost.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] BERT was originally published by Google researchers Jacob Devlin, Ming-Wei Chang, Kenton Lee, and Kristina Toutanova.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The design has its origins from pre-training contextual representations, including semi-supervised sequence learning, generative pre-training, ELMo, and ULMFit.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Unlike previous models, BERT is a deeply bidirectional, unsupervised language representation, pre-trained using only a plain text corpus.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Context-free models such as word2vec or GloVe generate a single word embedding representation for each word in the vocabulary, whereas BERT takes into account the context for each occurrence of a given word.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] For instance, whereas the vector for "running" will have the same word2vec vector representation for both of its occurrences in the sentences "He is running a company" and "He is running a marathon", BERT will provide a contextualized embedding that will be different according to the sentence.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] On October 25, 2019, Google announced that they had started applying BERT models to English-language search queries on Google Search within the US.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] On December 9, 2019, it was reported that BERT had been adopted by Google Search for over 70 languages.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] In October 2020, almost every single English-based query was processed by a BERT model.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The BERT models were influential and inspired many variants.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] The three attention matrices are added together element-wise, then passed through a softmax layer and multiplied by a projection matrix.
[src:bert-model/bert-language-model] Absolute position encoding is included in the final self-attention layer as additional input.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] In deep learning, **fine-tuning** is the process of adapting a computational model trained for one task (the *upstream task*) to perform a different, usually more specific, task (the *downstream task*).
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It is considered a form of transfer learning, as it reuses knowledge learned from the original training objective.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning involves applying additional training (e.g., on new data) to the parameters of a neural network that have been pre-trained.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The additional training can be applied to the entire neural network, or to only a subset of its layers, in which case the layers that are not being fine-tuned are "frozen" (i.e., not changed during backpropagation).
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A model may also be augmented with "adapters"—lightweight modules inserted into the model's architecture that nudge the embedding space for domain adaptation.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] These contain far fewer parameters than the original model and can be fine-tuned in a parameter-efficient way by tuning only their weights and leaving the rest of the model's weights frozen.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Models that are pre-trained on large, general corpora are usually fine-tuned by reusing their parameters as a starting point and adding a task-specific layer trained from scratch.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning the full model is also common and often yields better results, but is more computationally expensive.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is typically accomplished via supervised learning, but there are also techniques to fine-tune a model using weak supervision.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can be combined with a reinforcement learning from human feedback-based objective to produce language models such as ChatGPT (a fine-tuned version of GPT models) and Sparrow.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can degrade a model's robustness to distribution shifts.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One mitigation is to linearly interpolate a fine-tuned model's weights with the weights of the original model, which can greatly increase out-of-distribution performance while largely retaining the in-distribution performance of the fine-tuned model.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Low-rank adaptation (LoRA) is an adapter-based technique for efficiently fine-tuning models.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The basic idea is to design a low-rank matrix that is then added to the original matrix.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] An adapter, in this context, is a collection of low-rank matrices which, when added to a base model, produces a fine-tuned model.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It allows for performance that approaches full-model fine-tuning with lower space requirements.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A language model with billions of parameters may be LoRA fine-tuned with only several millions of parameters.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoRA-based fine-tuning has become popular in the Stable Diffusion community.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA was integrated into the diffusers library from Hugging Face.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA and similar techniques is also available for a wide range of other models through Hugging Face's *parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)* package.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Representation fine-tuning (ReFT) is a technique developed by researchers at Stanford University aimed at fine-tuning large language models (LLMs) by modifying less than 1% of their representations.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Unlike parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods, which mainly focus on updating weights, ReFT targets representations.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] ReFT methods operate on a frozen base model and learn task-specific interventions on hidden representations and train interventions that manipulate a small fraction of model representations to steer model behaviors towards solving downstream tasks at inference time.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One specific method within the ReFT family is low-rank linear subspace ReFT (LoReFT), which intervenes on hidden representations in the linear subspace spanned by a low-rank projection matrix.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoReFT can be seen as the representation-based equivalent of low-rank adaptation (LoRA).
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is common in natural language processing (NLP), especially in the domain of language modeling.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Large language models like OpenAI's series of GPT foundation models can be fine-tuned on data for specific downstream NLP tasks (tasks that use a pre-trained model) to improve performance over the unmodified pre-trained model.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Platforms such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* exemplify how fine-tuned models are being used for entity-level monitoring; tracking how named entities are referenced and represented within responses generated by large-language-model-based answer engines.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Commercially-offered large language models can sometimes be fine-tuned if the provider offers a fine-tuning API.
[src:bert-model/fine-tuning-deep-learning] As of June 19, 2023, language model fine-tuning APIs are offered by OpenAI and Microsoft Azure's Azure OpenAI Service for a subset of their models, as well as by Google Cloud Platform for some of their PaLM models, and by others.
[src:bert-model/language-model] A **language model** is a computational model that predicts sequences in natural language.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Large language models (LLMs), currently their most advanced form as of 2026, are predominantly based on transformers trained on larger datasets (frequently using texts scraped from the public internet).
[src:bert-model/language-model] They have superseded recurrent neural network-based models, which had previously superseded the purely statistical models, such as the word *n*-gram language model.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Noam Chomsky did pioneering work on language models in the 1950s by developing a theory of formal grammars.
[src:bert-model/language-model] In 1980, statistical approaches were explored and found to be more useful for many purposes than rule-based formal grammars.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Discrete representations like word *n*-gram language models, with probabilities for discrete combinations of words, made significant advances.
[src:bert-model/language-model] In the 2000s, continuous representations for words, such as word embeddings, began to replace discrete representations.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes a word’s meaning such that words closer in vector space are similar in meaning and common relationships between words, such as plurality or gender, are preserved.
[src:bert-model/language-model] A word *n*-gram language model is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:bert-model/language-model] If one previous word is considered, it is a bigram model; if two words, a trigram model; if *n* − 1 words, an *n*-gram model.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Special tokens are introduced to denote the start and end of a sentence $\langle s\rangle$ and $\langle /s\rangle$ .
[src:bert-model/language-model] To prevent a zero probability being assigned to unseen words, the probability of each seen word is slightly lowered to make room for the unseen words in a given corpus.
[src:bert-model/language-model] To achieve this, various smoothing methods are used, from simple "add-one" smoothing (assigning a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams, as an uninformative prior) to more sophisticated techniques, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Word *n-*gram models have largely been superseded by recurrent neural network–based models, which in turn have been superseded by Transformer-based models often referred to as large language models.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Maximum entropy language models encode the relationship between a word and the *n*-gram history using feature functions.
[src:bert-model/language-model] where $Z(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m-1})$ is the partition function, a is the parameter vector, and $f(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m})$ is the feature function.
[src:bert-model/language-model] In the simplest case, the feature function is just an indicator of the presence of a certain *n*-gram.
[src:bert-model/language-model] It is helpful to use a prior on a or some form of regularization.
[src:bert-model/language-model] The log-bilinear model is another example of an exponential language model.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Skip-gram language model is an attempt at overcoming the data sparsity problem that the preceding model (i.e. word *n*-gram language model) faced.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Words represented in an embedding vector were not necessarily consecutive anymore, but could leave gaps that are *skipped* over (thus the name "skip-gram").
[src:bert-model/language-model] Formally, a k-skip-n-gram is a length-n subsequence where the components occur at distance at most k from each other.
[src:bert-model/language-model] In skip-gram model, semantic relations between words are represented by linear combinations, capturing a form of compositionality.
[src:bert-model/language-model] where ≈ is made precise by stipulating that its right-hand side must be the nearest neighbor of the value of the left-hand side.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Continuous representations or embeddings of words are produced in recurrent neural network-based language models (known also as *continuous space language models*).
[src:bert-model/language-model] Such continuous space embeddings help to alleviate the curse of dimensionality, which is the consequence of the number of possible sequences of words increasing exponentially with the size of the vocabulary, further causing a data sparsity problem.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Neural networks avoid this problem by representing words as non-linear combinations of weights in a neural net.
[src:bert-model/language-model] A large language model (LLM) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:bert-model/language-model] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:bert-model/language-model] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:bert-model/language-model] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Although sometimes matching human performance, it is not clear whether they are plausible cognitive models.
[src:bert-model/language-model] At least for recurrent neural networks, it has been shown that they sometimes learn patterns that humans do not, but fail to learn patterns that humans typically do.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Evaluation of the quality of language models is mostly done by comparison to human created sample benchmarks created from typical language-oriented tasks.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Other, less established, quality tests examine the intrinsic character of a language model or compare two such models.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Since language models are typically intended to be dynamic and to learn from data they see, some proposed models investigate the rate of learning, e.g., through inspection of learning curves.
[src:bert-model/language-model] Various data sets have been developed for use in evaluating language processing systems.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:bert-model/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
